<LEADPARA>  For a decade now, Assemblyman John Vasconcellos has driven one of the rattiest
cars in Sacramento: a 1979 Olds cutlass convertible that recently reached the
grand old distance of 232,000 miles. A staffer on Ways and Means, Geoff Long,
jokes that the car had two engines, two tops, two interiors and only two car
washes. "It used to be that when you rode in the back of that car, you had to
take your clothes to the cleaner," Long explained. "He had socks you wouldn't
believe." As long as eight years ago, ex-Assemblyman Lou Pappan pestered
Vasconcellos to get himself better wheels. But Vasco -- to whom creature
comforts mean nothing -- refused. "It's served me well and saved the state
thousands of dollars," he explained. "Besides, it's got personality.";    So
it was news when Vasco last week junked the clunk and got himself a new car.
Using the legislature's $400-per-month auto allowance, he got a 1990 Olds
Cutlass convertible. His staff, sensing the best way to tell this story was
with humor, put out a press release announcing the change. For his part, Vasco
played it straight: "I plan to put 250,000 miles on this one," he said.  </LEADPARA>
