<LEADPARA>  For those who relish invective, one of the more inspiring exchanges occurred
recently between Assemblyman John Vasconcellos and Los Angeles County
Supervisor Pete Schabarum. Schabarum, you may remember, was the author of
Proposition 140, the initiative that imposed term limits and axed legislative
staffs. Last month, Vasconcellos told the press that he was thinking about
quitting the Assembly because of the hackles of the measure. "I don't see any
point in killing myself for people who apparently don't care if they have
decent government or not," said Vasco. His kicker: "The only reason for me to
stay is to outlast that idiot Schabarum.";    Schabarum responded last week
with a snotty two-page letter to Vasco. "I would have thought that someone
with your resources of self-esteem would have been able to weather through the
public's displeasure without any disturbance to the prescribed mellow mood."
He then went on to question what Vasco could do in private life, suggesting
that the assemblyman was out of touch. "I read your comments about quitting
not as a threat, but as a promise," Schabarum wrote. "And I challenge you here
and now to perform on it."  </LEADPARA>
